# Git Tutorial — From Zero to GitHub
### By Osama | April 2026

---

## What is Git?

Git is a **version control system** that runs on your computer. It tracks changes to your files over time, allowing you to:
- Save snapshots of your work (commits)
- Go back to any previous version
- Work on new features without risking your main code (branches)
- Collaborate with others (push/pull)

### Git vs GitHub vs GitLab

| Tool | What it is |
|------|-----------|
| **Git** | The tool on your PC — works offline |
| **GitHub** | A website that hosts your Git repos online |
| **GitLab** | Same as GitHub — used by universities and research institutes |

> Think of Git as Microsoft Word and GitHub/GitLab as OneDrive — you work locally, then upload to the cloud.

---

## Setup

### Step 1: Verify Git is installed
```bash
git --version
# Expected output: git version 2.x.x
```

### Step 2: Set your identity
```bash
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "youremail@example.com"
```

### Step 3: Verify your identity
```bash
git config --list
# Expected output:
# user.name=Your Name
# user.email=youremail@example.com
```

---

## Core Local Workflow

### Step 4: Create a new repository
```bash
mkdir my-first-repo
cd my-first-repo
git init
# Expected output: Initialized empty Git repository in .../my-first-repo/.git/
```

### Step 5: Create a file
```bash
echo "Hello, Git!" > hello.txt
```

### Step 6: Check status
```bash
git status
# Expected output:
# Untracked files:
#   hello.txt
```

> **Untracked** means Git can see the file but is NOT recording changes to it yet.

### Step 7: Stage your files
```bash
git add .
# The . means "stage everything in this folder"
```

```bash
git status
# Expected output:
# Changes to be committed:
#   new file: hello.txt
```

> **Staging** is like putting files in a box before sealing it. It gives you control over exactly what goes into each commit.

### Step 8: Make your first commit
```bash
git commit -m "My first commit"
# Expected output:
# [master (root-commit) a131e70] My first commit
# 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+)
```

> A **commit** is a permanent snapshot of your files at that moment. Always write a meaningful message!

### Step 9: View your history
```bash
git log
# Expected output:
# commit a131e708... (HEAD -> master)
# Author: Your Name <email>
# Date: ...
#     My first commit
```

### Step 10: Make a change and commit again
1. Open `hello.txt` and edit it
2. Save the file
3. Run:
```bash
git status        # Shows "modified: hello.txt"
git add .
git commit -m "Updated hello.txt"
git log           # Now shows 2 commits
```

### Step 11: Compare two commits
```bash
git diff <first-commit-id> <second-commit-id>
```

**Reading the diff output:**

| Symbol | Color | Meaning |
|--------|-------|---------|
| `+` | Green | Line was **added** |
| `-` | Red | Line was **deleted** |
| (none) | White | Line **unchanged** |

---

## Branches

A branch is a **parallel version** of your project. Use branches to experiment freely without affecting your main code.

**Real example for your thesis:**
- `master` — stable, working robot code
- `new-algorithm` — experimenting with a new grinding path
- `cv-testing` — testing OpenCV tool wear detection

### Step 12: Create and switch branches
```bash
git branch                    # List all branches (* = current)
git branch my-feature         # Create new branch
git checkout my-feature       # Switch to it
git branch                    # Verify (* is now on my-feature)
```

### Step 13: Work on your branch
```bash
echo "new feature" > feature.txt
git add .
git commit -m "added feature file"
git log                       # Shows new commit on my-feature
```

### Step 14: Switch back to master
```bash
git checkout master
ls                            # feature.txt is GONE — master is untouched!
```

> Git physically changes your folder contents when you switch branches! 🤯

### Step 15: Merge your branch into master
```bash
git checkout master           # Make sure you're on master
git merge my-feature          # Merge feature branch in
ls                            # feature.txt is now on master too!
```

**Visual representation:**
```
master      ●──●──────────●   ← after merge
                 \        /
my-feature        ●──────     ← merged in
```

---

## Connecting to GitHub / GitLab

### Step 16: Connect local repo to GitHub
```bash
git remote add origin https://github.com/your-username/your-repo.git
git remote -v                 # Verify connection
```

### Step 17: Push your code online (first time)
```bash
git push -u origin master
# -u sets GitHub as default destination (only needed first time!)
```

### Step 18: Push future changes
```bash
git add .
git commit -m "your message"
git push                      # No need for -u origin master anymore!
```

### Step 19: Pull updates from online
```bash
git pull                      # Downloads and applies online changes locally
```

> **Note:** `git status` only checks local changes — it won't tell you about online changes. Always run `git pull` to get the latest!

---

## The Complete Daily Workflow

```bash
git pull                      # 1. Get latest updates from online
# ... make your changes ...
git status                    # 2. Check what changed
git add .                     # 3. Stage your changes
git commit -m "description"   # 4. Save snapshot
git push                      # 5. Upload to online
```

---

## Quick Reference — All Commands

| Command | What it does |
|---------|-------------|
| `git init` | Initialize a new repo |
| `git status` | Check current changes |
| `git add .` | Stage all changes |
| `git add <file>` | Stage a specific file |
| `git commit -m ""` | Save a snapshot with a message |
| `git log` | View commit history |
| `git diff <id1> <id2>` | Compare two commits |
| `git branch` | List branches |
| `git branch <name>` | Create a new branch |
| `git checkout <name>` | Switch to a branch |
| `git merge <name>` | Merge a branch into current |
| `git remote add origin <url>` | Connect to GitHub/GitLab |
| `git push` | Upload commits online |
| `git pull` | Download online changes |
| `git clone <url>` | Download a full repo |

---

## Tips

- Always write **meaningful commit messages** — future you will thank you!
- Commit **often** — small snapshots are better than one giant commit
- Always `git pull` before starting work to avoid conflicts
- Use **branches** for any new feature or experiment — never work directly on master for important projects
- Your commit history is your project's **diary** — make it readable!

---

